WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Created by ©Yozuki  |  #VisitUs  t.me/Yozukilk

2
00:00:40.210 --> 00:00:43.360
Hey! Make it stop!

3
00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:46.990
What in the world <i>was</i> that?!

4
00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:06.340
16bit Sensation:
Another Layer

5
00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:18.700
16bit Sensation:
Another Layer

6
00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:29.500
"Echo"

7
00:02:32.130 --> 00:02:34.840
Sensei! What's with him?!

8
00:02:37.030 --> 00:02:39.760
Looks like a guest has dropped 
in through the ceiling.

9
00:02:40.530 --> 00:02:43.760
Is that how guests are supposed to come in?

10
00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:47.400
I heard they used a thing 
called an "entrance"!

11
00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:50.280
Perhaps you could call it a 
multidimensional entrance.

12
00:02:57.540 --> 00:02:59.340
Ah, he's awake!

13
00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:05.130
What year are we in right now?

14
00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:08.620
It's the year 1985.

15
00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:11.820
1985?

16
00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:38.820
Latest
Model!

17
00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:40.070
Recommended

18
00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:41.100
<i>Where is it?</i>

19
00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:43.400
<i>Not that!</i>

20
00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:46.450
Where could it be?!

21
00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:49.580
Latest model!

22
00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:49.570
There!

23
00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:53.460
The PC-9801 U!

24
00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:58.500
Released in May 1985, it's the first 
model with 3.5" floppy drives!

25
00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:00.200
Which means...

26
00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:01.850
What?!

27
00:04:01.850 --> 00:04:04.670
It really is the year 1985!

28
00:04:04.670 --> 00:04:07.140
Amazing!

29
00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:16.580
By the way, what is this place?

30
00:04:16.580 --> 00:04:22.000
This is Echosoft, a small, brand-new 
software company in Akihabara.

31
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:23.020
Waah!

32
00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:25.990
<i>When I opened the video game case,</i>

33
00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:28.020
<i>there was a bright light and 
I traveled back in time.</i>

34
00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:31.500
Gogo no Tenshi-tachi

35
00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:32.020
Gogo no Tenshi-tachi<i> is a game from 1985.</i>

36
00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:35.860
<i>In other words, you're sent back to the 
release year of the game you open.</i>

37
00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:38.130
<i>Is that how it works?</i>

38
00:04:39.190 --> 00:04:41.360
<i>And this place...</i>

39
00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:44.910
<i>It's the Alcohol Soft building!</i>

40
00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:49.630
<i>This place was a game studio even 
before Dad opened up his shop here?</i>

41
00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:53.720
<i>But how do I get back to the 
world that I came from?</i>

42
00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:57.150
<i>How did Konoha go back, again?</i>

43
00:05:00.110 --> 00:05:01.220
Mamoru-san.

44
00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:03.350
How about it?

45
00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:06.150
Would you like to make games with us?

46
00:05:06.150 --> 00:05:07.210
Huh?

47
00:05:07.210 --> 00:05:12.530
The truth is, we began creating something 
called "bishojo games" just the other day.

48
00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:16.230
However, we don't have any 
clue on what makes a good one.

49
00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:17.170
Indeed!

50
00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:22.560
Therefore, Mamoru-san, could 
we ask you to help us?

51
00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:28.960
On one condition.

52
00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:30.650
A PC-98.

53
00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:32.980
Let me use a PC-98.

54
00:05:32.980 --> 00:05:35.110
I'd be happy to work for you then.

55
00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:37.140
Very well.

56
00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:39.800
I forgot to introduce myself.

57
00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:40.480
Hm?

58
00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:44.000
I'm the head of Echosoft, Echo.

59
00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:48.870
I'm an Echosoft employee, Echo!

60
00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:50.360
Okay, Mamoru-san.

61
00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:52.850
We'll have you start working 
for us right away.

62
00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:54.790
Sure.

63
00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:05.380
<i>I started working part-time at Echosoft,</i>

64
00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:08.360
<i>a company I came across when 
I traveled back in time.</i>

65
00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.090
<i>Basically the exact same 
thing that Konoha did.</i>

66
00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:16.550
<i>The people at this company know 
my name for some reason,</i>

67
00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:18.520
<i>and had no qualms in 
letting me work for them.</i>

68
00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:22.710
<i>I can't help but worry how 
Konoha's game will turn out,</i>

69
00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:28.730
<i>but if I'm in the year 1985, you could 
say that time has basically stopped.</i>

70
00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.360
<i>Nothing will come out of worrying about it.</i>

71
00:06:32.450 --> 00:06:35.030
<i>Since I don't know how to get back,</i>

72
00:06:35.030 --> 00:06:37.370
<i>I had no choice but to stay here.</i>

73
00:06:39.990 --> 00:06:43.100
<i>That said, Echosoft is a strange company.</i>

74
00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:47.810
<i>They call themselves a game studio, 
but there are only two people working here.</i>

75
00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:50.880
<i>What's more, the president's 
name is also Echo.</i>

76
00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:53.500
<i>His assistant's name is Echo, too.</i>

77
00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:56.060
<i>Even their dog's name is Echo.</i>

78
00:06:56.060 --> 00:06:57.260
<i>You can't be serious.</i>

79
00:06:56.060 --> 00:06:57.980
Echo

80
00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:01.770
<i>Well, I'm not one to butt 
in on other people's business.</i>

81
00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:09.230
<i>Since I've been hired part-time, 
I'll put in my wage's worth.</i>

82
00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:12.150
<i>Game programming is a part of my duties.</i>

83
00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:16.270
<i>The president, Echo One, gets an 
astounding amount of work done,</i>

84
00:07:16.270 --> 00:07:18.760
<i>and he develops games 
at an incredible speed.</i>

85
00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:31.000
<i>Graphic artist, scenario 
writer, sound composer,</i>

86
00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.770
<i>not to mention programmer.</i>

87
00:07:32.770 --> 00:07:34.830
<i>Echo One has taken on all of those roles.</i>

88
00:07:35.930 --> 00:07:36.850
Echosoft Bishojo Game vol.

89
00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:39.430
<i>Well, that wasn't too uncommon in the 80s.</i>

90
00:07:36.850 --> 00:07:40.060
Echosoft Bishojo Game vol.

91
00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:45.220
<i>This is an old technique called 
"cling wrap scanning".</i>

92
00:07:45.770 --> 00:07:47.920
<i>You copy the line art, like this...</i>

93
00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:51.580
<i>and then trace over it in a graphics editor.</i>

94
00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:53.030
<i>No mouse involved.</i>

95
00:07:59.330 --> 00:08:02.520
<i>Here, he's actually composing 
the background music.</i>

96
00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:06.100
<i>Music Macro Language, or MML for short,</i>

97
00:08:06.100 --> 00:08:09.790
<i>is a specialized description language that 
he's using to type out the musical score.</i>

98
00:08:10.080 --> 00:08:13.070
<i>You can also use dedicated 
programs to compose music,</i>

99
00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:16.580
<i>but for some people,
writing MML directly is much faster.</i>

100
00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:21.230
<i>To draw the characters, he's using a 
special tool called a pattern editor.</i>

101
00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:24.720
<i>As you can see, he can use it to 
make pixel art of the characters,</i>

102
00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.170
<i>and it also allows you to 
create animations for them.</i>

103
00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:30.400
Hey, do you have a minute?

104
00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:32.270
Yes, what is it?

105
00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:34.460
How come you're not using any green?

106
00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.770
There are only eight 
colors available to use.

107
00:08:36.770 --> 00:08:38.630
No, I know that much.

108
00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:41.840
This character has blue armor.

109
00:08:42.170 --> 00:08:44.960
I'll use green for a different character.

110
00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:45.960
Ah.

111
00:08:46.270 --> 00:08:49.680
So I guess this black part is 
supposed to be the shadow, then?

112
00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:50.750
That's right.

113
00:08:51.530 --> 00:08:53.520
Can you let me try something?

114
00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:55.180
Sure...

115
00:08:57.770 --> 00:08:58.850
How's that?

116
00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:00.480
Well, well.

117
00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:02.740
It looks just like a commercial game.

118
00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:04.650
This is what's called dithering.

119
00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:07.170
Well, I'm just going off what I've seen.

120
00:09:08.510 --> 00:09:11.940
Mamoru-san, could you teach 
me some other things as well?

121
00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:13.950
Yeah.

122
00:09:13.950 --> 00:09:15.620
Thank you very much.

123
00:09:16.810 --> 00:09:21.080
For example, there's no need to 
use the PSG for sound effects.

124
00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:22.750
If you use system beeps like this...

125
00:09:23.550 --> 00:09:25.250
I see, I see.

126
00:09:26.150 --> 00:09:29.850
You're a programmer, but you 
can do all sorts of stuff.

127
00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:31.540
Of course I can.

128
00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:34.470
Programmers are the kings 
of game development.

129
00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:38.850
In the past, it used to be that programmers 
would have to do everything by themselves.

130
00:09:40.110 --> 00:09:43.260
<i>Incidentally, the games 
we're making are for PC-88.</i>

131
00:09:44.390 --> 00:09:46.310
Keep It Neat & Tidy

132
00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:46.310
<i>This may be a shady game company,</i>

133
00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:49.140
<i>but what they're doing is no 
different from a normal studio.</i>

134
00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:49.150
Keep It Neat & Tidy

135
00:09:49.530 --> 00:09:51.740
<i>However, their speed is 
on a different level.</i>

136
00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:57.760
<i>Echo One never goes through trial and 
error, or makes any corrections.</i>

137
00:09:58.100 --> 00:09:59.520
<i>It may sound absurd,</i>

138
00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:02.570
<i>but in just one day, he can complete 
a surprisingly hefty game.</i>

139
00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:09.330
Echosoft Bishojo Game vol. 39

140
00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:08.860
<i>Instant beyond belief.</i>

141
00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:11.230
<i>His assistant, Echo Two,</i>

142
00:10:11.230 --> 00:10:15.840
<i>always wears weird clothes and asks me 
to give her a score on how cute she is.</i>

143
00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:17.490
Mamoru-kun!

144
00:10:17.490 --> 00:10:19.520
How many points do I get today?

145
00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:23.550
<i>I don't really get it, so I 
just make up random numbers.</i>

146
00:10:23.550 --> 00:10:25.610
<i>Apparently this is also part of my job.</i>

147
00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:55.920
Maybe I can just stay here...

148
00:10:58.760 --> 00:10:59.990
Guess not.

149
00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:21.910
Imagination

150
00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:12.620
Do you really need this many TVs to watch?

151
00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:14.320
One should be more than enough.

152
00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:15.890
It's all just the same program.

153
00:11:15.890 --> 00:11:18.340
Do they look the same to you?

154
00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:21.540
To me, they all look quite different.

155
00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:30.280
An utter failure, it seems.

156
00:11:33.010 --> 00:11:34.500
What's this?

157
00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:38.300
This is a device to measure 
the energy that a game has.

158
00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:40.050
Gogo no Tenshi-tachi

159
00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:41.520
An interesting game contains lots of energy.

160
00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:45.020
Huh...

161
00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:46.700
What an odd device.

162
00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:51.120
The games that I make are 
completely devoid of energy.

163
00:11:51.510 --> 00:11:55.550
Well, I don't know whether 
fun translates into energy,

164
00:11:56.260 --> 00:11:59.650
but I can't tell from the design of 
the box that it would be any fun.

165
00:11:56.270 --> 00:12:00.280
Echosoft Bishojo
Game vol. 39

166
00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:02.460
Is that something that you imagine?

167
00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:04.980
How can you <i>not</i> imagine it?

168
00:12:04.980 --> 00:12:07.650
I don't have the power to imagine anything.

169
00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:10.670
I came from a place where 
imagination doesn't exist.

170
00:12:10.670 --> 00:12:12.400
Therefore, I don't understand it.

171
00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:15.780
Every time, my calculations are correct,

172
00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:17.750
but when I actually create a game,

173
00:12:17.750 --> 00:12:20.590
it doesn't have any of the thermal 
power that I'd expected.

174
00:12:21.250 --> 00:12:23.720
To learn about this thing 
called imagination...

175
00:12:24.660 --> 00:12:27.310
That's why I'm creating these games.

176
00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:30.140
Neat & Tidy

177
00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:33.140
Mamoru-kun!

178
00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:33.650
Hm?

179
00:12:34.090 --> 00:12:36.510
How many points do I get today?

180
00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:45.420
<i>I was surprised at the idea of anyone in the 
world completely lacking an imagination,</i>

181
00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:49.730
<i>but teaching someone what imagination 
was turned out to be fairly difficult.</i>

182
00:12:55.120 --> 00:12:57.870
It doesn't make any sense 
to not have an imagination.

183
00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:01.210
You know what a donut tastes like, right?

184
00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:03.950
For the ones that I've eaten, I do.

185
00:13:04.350 --> 00:13:06.970
These two donuts taste basically the same.

186
00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:10.590
Knowing that, you should be able 
to imagine how this one tastes.

187
00:13:11.220 --> 00:13:13.310
That's not imagination.

188
00:13:13.310 --> 00:13:15.720
It's reasoning based on experience.

189
00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:17.930
No, that's not my point.

190
00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:19.220
Um...

191
00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:22.330
Now <i>I'm</i> getting confused here...

192
00:13:22.940 --> 00:13:24.160
Mamoru-san.

193
00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:27.960
Your kind have the ability to feel 
that something is interesting.

194
00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:32.250
You can sense how other people 
feel, as if it was yourself.

195
00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:35.080
Imagination

196
00:13:32.250 --> 00:13:35.070
In other words, that's imagination.

197
00:13:35.510 --> 00:13:38.400
You can explain it to me, 
but not understand it yourself?

198
00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:42.120
This is nothing more than analysis.

199
00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:44.160
I wasn't using my imagination.

200
00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:46.220
Hmm...

201
00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:52.150
Imagination.

202
00:13:53.060 --> 00:13:55.130
What <i>is</i> imagination?

203
00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:02.040
<i>One day, Echo Two disappeared.</i>

204
00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:05.530
<i>And a full week passed without her return.</i>

205
00:14:11.070 --> 00:14:13.410
Two's been missing for a while.

206
00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:14.540
You're right.

207
00:14:14.540 --> 00:14:16.180
Is that all you have to say?

208
00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:17.860
Aren't you worried about her?!

209
00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:18.840
Worried?

210
00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:20.380
What is that?

211
00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:22.730
She vanished under unnatural circumstances.

212
00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:24.800
What if she's in danger right now?

213
00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:26.780
Echo's just fine.

214
00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:30.470
There's zero risk of her being in danger.

215
00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:32.300
Is she really okay?

216
00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:33.240
Yes.

217
00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:36.380
That said, it sure is inconvenient 
without her around.

218
00:14:39.850 --> 00:14:41.690
I'm going to go look for Two.

219
00:14:50.860 --> 00:14:55.870
Echosoft Bishojo Game

220
00:14:56.990 --> 00:15:02.040
I wonder what kind of games 
Mamoru-san finds interesting.

221
00:15:09.010 --> 00:15:10.540
Where have you been?

222
00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:12.630
Mamoru-kun!

223
00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:15.050
What are <i>you</i> doing here?

224
00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:16.470
Don't give me that.

225
00:15:16.470 --> 00:15:18.790
You didn't come back, 
so I came looking for you.

226
00:15:18.790 --> 00:15:20.140
Why?

227
00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:21.910
Why, you ask...

228
00:15:23.080 --> 00:15:26.570
Well, I guess it's no big deal 
since I ran into you here,

229
00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:30.120
but of course I'd be worried, after you went 
missing for a week without a word!

230
00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:32.570
Worried?

231
00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:34.410
What does "worried" mean?!

232
00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:37.740
What have you been up to over the past week?

233
00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:40.820
I went on a walk with Echo!

234
00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:44.110
That's one hell of a trek.

235
00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:46.240
Okay, I'm heading back.

236
00:15:58.180 --> 00:15:59.640
Mamoru-kun!

237
00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:02.100
I'll go back with you!

238
00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:21.900
Mamoru-kun!

239
00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:24.920
How many points do I get today?

240
00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:46.550
Akerue!

241
00:16:46.930 --> 00:16:47.780
Huh?

242
00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:49.060
Akerue!

243
00:17:04.870 --> 00:17:06.090
Sensei.

244
00:17:06.090 --> 00:17:09.390
I understand what imagination is now.

245
00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.620
What is it, then?

246
00:17:12.620 --> 00:17:14.350
I can't explain it.

247
00:17:14.350 --> 00:17:17.000
I don't have any way of 
putting it into words.

248
00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.250
Is that so?

249
00:17:18.250 --> 00:17:21.890
Perhaps I've come to an 
understanding of sorts as well.

250
00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:26.130
Let us merge into one.

251
00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:45.120
Please come up to the rooftop

252
00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:51.840
Were there always this many stairs?

253
00:17:56.150 --> 00:17:58.380
Up here, Mamoru-san.

254
00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:11.200
Hello, Mamoru-san.

255
00:18:11.820 --> 00:18:14.100
What's with the get-up?

256
00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:16.670
I was performing maintenance on the device.

257
00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:19.620
You can see all of Akihabara up here.

258
00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:22.740
Did this building always go up this high?

259
00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:25.500
Mamoru-san.

260
00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:28.470
What do you think about this town?

261
00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:32.040
Compared to '99, it's not as bright.

262
00:18:33.320 --> 00:18:35.050
I can see it.

263
00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:43.190
The abundance of energy 
gathering in this town.

264
00:18:44.620 --> 00:18:47.990
In time, this will become a place 
where anything is possible.

265
00:18:47.990 --> 00:18:50.110
That's the future that awaits this town.

266
00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:54.280
This isn't reasoning based 
on my observations.

267
00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:56.110
It's what I imagine.

268
00:18:56.110 --> 00:18:58.650
You gained the power to imagine things?

269
00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:02.680
Mamoru-san.

270
00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:06.030
What do you think about the 
human power of imagination?

271
00:19:06.030 --> 00:19:08.780
Beats me. I'm an engineer.

272
00:19:09.130 --> 00:19:14.550
I let people like Konoha or Kyonshi 
deal with cultural ideas like that.

273
00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:17.650
A world where fantastic 
monsters roam freely.

274
00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:20.010
A paradise floating in the sky.

275
00:19:20.010 --> 00:19:21.930
The dead rising from their graves.

276
00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:23.970
A place that exists nowhere.

277
00:19:24.410 --> 00:19:28.340
The power to recall things that 
don't exist, and give them form.

278
00:19:29.220 --> 00:19:32.970
All humans have the power to 
create things of that nature,

279
00:19:32.970 --> 00:19:36.130
as well as to experience them.

280
00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:38.980
Perhaps that's what makes them human.

281
00:19:39.310 --> 00:19:40.990
Don't you think?

282
00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:43.890
The games that we created,

283
00:19:43.890 --> 00:19:46.870
along with manga, novels, movies,

284
00:19:46.870 --> 00:19:49.700
countless tales dating 
back to ancient times,

285
00:19:50.130 --> 00:19:53.880
not to mention religions, 
nations, communities,

286
00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:56.690
dreams, hopes, and despair.

287
00:19:56.690 --> 00:20:01.170
All of these are concepts created 
through a shared imagination.

288
00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:05.930
You can't just explain every 
single thing with imagination!

289
00:20:05.930 --> 00:20:08.090
Sounds like <i>you're</i> the one 
imagining things now.

290
00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:10.540
I know that you're well aware, Mamoru-san.

291
00:20:10.540 --> 00:20:14.510
Of the energy that gathers when 
imagination is unleashed.

292
00:20:15.390 --> 00:20:19.770
You should have experienced 
it not too long ago.

293
00:20:19.770 --> 00:20:21.060
Isn't that right?

294
00:20:27.780 --> 00:20:28.800
An earthquake?

295
00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:31.410
An exceedingly rare kind of lifeform.

296
00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:36.910
Through their imagination, humans 
become multidimensional beings,

297
00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:40.110
and access present, past, future...

298
00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:43.560
Different space-times, different events...

299
00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:48.520
Gaining massive energy from 
quantum possibilities.

300
00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:53.010
Upheld by thermodynamics as well.

301
00:20:55.350 --> 00:20:56.190
You people...

302
00:20:56.930 --> 00:20:58.580
What exactly <i>are</i> you?

303
00:20:58.970 --> 00:21:01.000
Your kind are the future.

304
00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.430
As well as the past.

305
00:21:02.430 --> 00:21:04.030
And the present.

306
00:21:05.070 --> 00:21:09.030
Imagination has the power to 
alter both time and space.

307
00:21:09.030 --> 00:21:13.010
Imagination is what defines reality.

308
00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:21.180
I'm a supporter of the 
games that you all have made.

309
00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:28.810
I know we'll meet again someday.

310
00:21:41.450 --> 00:21:43.110
Theme for our next title

311
00:21:41.450 --> 00:21:43.110
Interesting

312
00:21:41.450 --> 00:21:43.110
Game 
that will 
earn one 
billion yen

313
00:21:41.450 --> 00:21:43.110
We can do it!

314
00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:50.860
I see.

315
00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:52.570
So that's what it's like.

316
00:22:00.510 --> 00:22:04.010
I left everything I bought behind...

317
00:23:34.970 --> 00:23:39.970
"See You Later!"↵

318
00:23:34.970 --> 00:23:39.970
HELP for help

